you smell band aids, if you smell asphalt,
you smell asphalt and I'm not necessarily

00:07:29.199 --> 00:07:34.009
saying these are bad things in beer; but have
your, make sure your mind is open to these

00:07:34.009 --> 00:07:38.530
flavors in beer. And really with beer it is
just a matter of paying attention. Because

00:07:38.530 --> 00:07:42.039
people don't pay attention to beer, people
pound beer. You know we've all done a keg

00:07:42.039 --> 00:07:45.531
stand. I hope, do it once, put it on your
bucket list if you haven't --

00:07:45.531 --> 00:07:47.349
&gt;&gt;Hallie: you could, you could see what we,
we both grew up on...

00:07:47.349 --> 00:07:48.349
[laughter]

00:07:48.349 --> 00:07:50.729
&gt;&gt;Hallie: we've both mentioned, like pounding
beers and keg stands.

00:07:50.729 --> 00:07:55.900
&gt;&gt;Christina: so anyway so we're gonna go into
really quickly what the uh, ingredients of

00:07:55.900 --> 00:08:01.499
beer. Most people have no idea what beer even
is. I still don't know what Diet Coke is

00:08:01.499 --> 00:08:03.669
&gt;&gt;Haille: No one does. It's scary.

00:08:03.669 --> 00:08:04.669
[laughter]

00:08:04.669 --> 00:08:09.379
&gt;&gt;Christina: Um, but basically beer consists
of four ingredients. Obviously there is water,

00:08:09.379 --> 00:08:14.860
which makes up about 95% of beer; there is
an ingredient called malts, which are grains

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:20.960
and that is what provides the fermentable
sugars in beer. Um, there is yeast, which

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:27.249
is a single cell organism which eats the sugars
and malts and creates alcohol and CO2 and

00:08:27.249 --> 00:08:32.010
then there is hops, which provide a bitterness
and balance in beer.

00:08:32.010 --> 00:08:37.340
&gt;&gt;Hallie: So the way that these work together
and make a very happy beverage is that the

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:42.409
yeast eats the malts and creates the alcohol
and CO2. So that's, the that's the science

00:08:42.409 --> 00:08:45.970
behind beer, that's what we call the birds
and the bees of beer. So, now that you know

00:08:45.970 --> 00:08:50.980
those two things, the ingredients and how
beer is made, you know more than like 90%

00:08:50.980 --> 00:08:55.240
of the population, which is sad. But is true,
like people if you ask someone on the street

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:57.510
"What is in beer?" They are like "I don't
know."

00:08:57.510 --> 00:09:01.290
They might say barley because you hear that
word but you know people just aren't familiar

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:02.290
with how it's made --

00:09:02.290 --> 00:09:06.560
&gt;&gt;Christina: and each one of the ingredients
parts many different permutations of flavors

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:11.620
in beer. For instance there are 100s of different
varietals of hops: there are hops that are

00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:15.730
grassy; there are hops that are really bitter;
there are hops that are urbascious; there

00:09:15.730 --> 00:09:20.950
are hops that are citrusy. Um, with malts
uh, the malts are the grains, so there's rye,

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:25.970
there's oats, there's wheat, there's rice,
um, and all of these and many other grains

00:09:25.970 --> 00:09:30.500
and all these grains can be roasted to varying
levels. They can be roasted really dark where

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:35.800
they take on chocolaty, toasty, nutty qualities
and they can be dried very quickly where they

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:41.130
are very pale and have kind of biscuity, bready
qualities. Um . . . also water plays a difference.

00:09:41.130 --> 00:09:45.630
You have very hard water with a lot of minerals
and those kinds of waters are better for stronger

00:09:45.630 --> 00:09:50.339
flavored beers, more bitter beers. You can
have very soft water like in Munich, is a

00:09:50.339 --> 00:09:54.680
good example of very soft water and beers
that come from there are very light, pilsner,

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:59.220
Czech style you know light lagers. Things
like that, and am I missing, oh and yah then

00:09:59.220 --> 00:10:00.220
there is yeast.

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:01.220
&gt;&gt;Hallie: Yeast.

00:10:01.220 --> 00:10:02.510
&gt;&gt;Christina: --which the next you're going
to have is going to be a good example of what

00:10:02.510 --> 00:10:05.290
yeast can do; so open the Franziskaner the
Hefeweizen.

00:10:05.290 --> 00:10:12.560
&gt;&gt;Hallie: And you can dump your um, beers
in the sand castle bucket, um, you don't have

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:16.320
to finish. You, you may not like all the beers.
It's ok, you don't have to pretend like you

00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:17.339
like them.

00:10:17.339 --> 00:10:20.900
[audience chatting going on the background]

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:25.199
&gt;&gt;Hallie: So, uh, so with those four ingredients
there's a also um obviously there are many

00:10:25.199 --> 00:10:28.600
different ways you could put these together.
So you could have you could have a yeast that

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:33.720
brings out a lot of fruit and a dark chocolaty
malt so you're having a combination of some,

00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:38.510
some fruity coffee flavors or you could have
something that is a little lighter, a little

00:10:38.510 --> 00:10:43.449
biscuit; so you can see there are a plethora
of flavors in beer. You will never run out

00:10:43.449 --> 00:10:47.570
of new combinations between the hops, the
malt, and the yeast so we will never run out

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:51.670
of, of a new variety of craft beer which is
what makes it kind of exciting.

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:55.750
So get your nose in there again, make sure
you are not just thowin' it down, thowin'

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:58.140
back. Smell it. You smell a difference?

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:03.040
&gt;&gt;Christina: So, this is a good example of
yeast what yeast can do in beer. So, there

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:08.760
are also many hundreds of different hybrids
of yeast, some are proprietary, some people

00:11:08.760 --> 00:11:13.420
have developed their own specific hybrid of
yeast that has specific flavors that they

00:11:13.420 --> 00:11:20.510
want for their beer. Uh, this is a good example
because this German beer has to uh, falls

00:11:20.510 --> 00:11:22.360
under the law called Reinheitsgebot.

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:23.820
&gt;&gt;Hallie: I'm so glad you say that because
I don't know how to say that.

00:11:23.820 --> 00:11:27.910
&gt;&gt;Christina: It's a hard word, Reinheitsgebot
,which is the German purity law, which means

00:11:27.910 --> 00:11:31.870
that you can only have four ingredients in
beer; you can't add anything else other than

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:34.279
water, yeast, malt, and hops.

